\begin_layout Standard
My graduate career has been focused on neutron detection - specifically
 on designing, developing, and applying the Tensioned Metastable Fluid Detector
 (TMFD).
 The dissertation I will be defending within the next two months has focused
 on the application of these detectors to active interrogation of cargo
 for interdiction of special nuclear materials.
 The detectors are highly sensitive to neutrons, and able to operate in
 high fields of dose (tested above 
\begin_inset Formula $1000\;\mathrm{{\nicefrac{R}{hr}}}$
\end_inset

).
 My design of the system won our lab the Best Demo Award at the IEEE Sensors
 conference in 2016, and my application of these detectors to active interrogati
on won me both the ANS Winter Meeting Young Members' Group Best Paper Award
 in 2016 and the DoE's Innovations in Nuclear Technology R&D award in 2017.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
However, the TMFD is not the detector for every application, particularly
 those requiring fast temporal response, or those at high temperature.
 Fortunately, through the course of my PhD, I've gained experience with
 many other methods of detection.
 I've designed and performed experiments with liquid scintillators, ion
 chambers, germanium detectors, lanthanum bromide detectors, sodium iodide
 detectors; and modern electronics and data acquisition systems associated
 with these detectors.
 I've also designed and built data acquisition systems for our detectors
 - I built a (somewhat) fast data acquisistion system that lived onboard
 our spinning Centrifugally Tensioned Metastable Fluid Detector to detect
 the acoustic traces from neutron interactions.
 This had lead into a new capability that may allow us to help weakly interactin
g massive particle detection efforts by discriminating alpha events from
 WIMP events.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
I've also gained a lot of experience with monte carlo modeling of particle
 transport.
 The bulk of my work has used MCNP based codes, including MCNP6.1, MCNPX,
